am Firdos Square Statues face 2003-04-09.jpg\n| position = center\n| size = 300\n| color = #F5F5F5\n| border = 2\n| color_border = black\n| spacing = 3\n| foot_montage =  \n}}\n| caption     = From left to right: Marines of the U.S. 1st Marine Regiment escort Iraqi prisoners of war; a convoy of U.S. military vehicles in a sandstorm; U.S. soldiers watch an enemy building in [[Samawah]] burn; Iraqi civilians cheer as a statue of Saddam Hussein is toppled.\n| date        = 20 March&nbsp;\u2013 1 May 2003<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1= 3|day1= 20|year1= 2003|month2= 5|day2= 1|year2= 2003}})\n| place       = Iraq\n| casus       = The officially stated sole trigger for the invasion was the assertion by the U.S. and other allied governments that Iraq had failed comply with 17 successive [[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]] resolutions calling upon the country to disarm itself of [[Weapon of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]]; Iraq also expelled U.N. weapons inspectors from its country.\n| result      = Coalition operational success\n* <!--([[Saddam Hussein]]'s [[Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party \u2013 Iraq Region|Ba'ath Party]])-->[[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraqi Ba'athist]] government deposed\n* Occupation of Iraq [[History of Iraq (2003\u20132011)|until 2011]]<ref name=un>{{cite news|title= Security Council endorses formation of sovereign interim government in Iraq; welcomes end of occupation by 30 June, democratic elections by January 2005|url= https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2004/sc8117.doc.htm|publisher= United Nations|date= 8 June 2004|access-date= 5 June 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140923210327/http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2004/sc8117.doc.htm|archive-date= 23 September 2014|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Al Maliki I Government|New Iraqi government]] established\n* Beginning of the [[Iraq War]]\n| combatant1  = '''Coalition forces:'''<br />\n{{flag|United States}}<br />\n{{flag|United Kingdom}}<br />\n{{flag|Australia}}<br />\n{{flag|Poland}}\n\n----\n''With military support from:''<br />\n[[Iraqi National Congress]]<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A42859-2003Apr6.html |title= U.S. Airlifts Iraqi Exile Force For Duties Near Nasiriyah |work= Washington Post |date= 7 April 2003 |accessdate= 13 September 2009 |first= Bradley |last= Graham |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070808031321/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A42859-2003Apr6.html |archive-date= 8 August 2007 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= John Pike |url= http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2003/iraq-030314-afps03.htm |title= Free Iraqi Forces Committed to Democracy, Rule of Law \u2013 DefenseLink |publisher= Globalsecurity.org |date= 14 March 2003 |accessdate= 13 September 2009|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090910192110/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2003/iraq-030314-afps03.htm|archivedate= 10 September 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"USNewsandworldreport\"/><br />\n{{flagdeco|Iraqi Kurdistan}} [[Peshmerga]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the KDP.svg}} [[Kurdistan Democratic Party|KDP]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of PUK.png}} [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Ba'athist Iraq}}\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Hejaz 1917.svg}} [[Arab]] volunteers<ref name=\"Ghattas20030414\">{{cite news|title= Syrians join Iraq 'jihad'|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2947233.stm|author= Kim Ghattas|date= 14 April 2003|work= BBC News|accessdate= 29 October 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110921180850/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/2947233.stm|archive-date= 21 September 2011|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Arab volunteers to Iraq: 'token' act or the makings of another Afghan jihad?|url= http://www.lebanonwire.com/0304/03040113DS.asp|accessdate= 29 October 2011 |url-status= dead|arc